My compact understanding of the whole video
The demo is basically a “memory stack” that turns your Obsidian vault into Claude Code’s searchable long-term memory.

Obsidian = the source of truth (Markdown notes, daily logs, transcripts, project docs, etc.).

Claude Code = working memory (it remembers within a session, until context limits / new terminal / next day).

QMD = retrieval layer (a fast local search/index over your vault; supports keyword/BM25, vector/semantic, and hybrid).

“Recall” skill = the glue (a command Claude can run that pulls the right notes + past Claude sessions into the current context).

The key problem being solved: Claude Code normally doesn’t “remember” across projects/days because it doesn’t automatically search and load your vault. Without retrieval, you end up doing slow brute-force “go search everything,” burning time/tokens and getting noisy results.

So the workflow is:

Index your vault (often split into “collections” like daily notes, Claude sessions, transcripts, etc.).

Export Claude Code conversations to clean Markdown notes (so they become part of the same knowledge base).

Keep the index fresh automatically (a hook runs when you end a session: export → reindex).

When you start working, use Recall to instantly load relevant context by:

time (“yesterday”, “last week”),

topic (BM25/semantic search),

or graph (visual map of sessions ↔ files).

Result: you stop re-explaining yourself, and your notes stop being passive storage—they become an active, queryable memory.

Specific benefits of Obsidian + Claude Code (as demoed)
1) Fast, high-signal “memory” across days/projects
Instead of Claude scanning hundreds of files every time, retrieval returns the top relevant notes in seconds, which Claude can then use immediately.

Benefits:

Dramatically less “cold start” friction when resuming work.

Less context window waste (Claude reads only the best snippets).

Much cheaper in tokens and faster than brute-force reading.

2) Your Claude sessions become first-class knowledge
Each Claude Code conversation is saved as a Markdown note that also links to every file it touched. That creates a permanent audit trail:

What decisions did we make?

What files changed?

What was the rationale?

Then those sessions are indexed too, so you can search your past thinking, not just your notes.

3) Better search than grep for “human questions”
The demo compares approaches:

grep / brute force: noisy and slow; matches literal strings across tons of files.

BM25 keyword search: fast and usually “good enough” for structured notes.

vector semantic search: finds meaning even when keywords differ (great for messy brain dumps / transcripts).

hybrid: often best ranking, sometimes slower.

Practical takeaway (from the demo): start with BM25, add semantic/hybrid where fuzzier meaning matters.

4) New kinds of reflection/analysis become possible
Once transcripts + daily notes are indexed, you can ask things like:

“Which days was I happiest and why?”

“Where am I consistently frustrated or uncertain?”

